    <bioghist>
      <head>Historical Note</head>
      <p>The origins of the 38th Street Open Door Congregational Church began at the corner of
        Fourth Avenue and 38th Street in Minneapolis as a Sunday school and mission. In 1896, it was
        decided to organize into a full church, the 38th Street Union Church. The following year,
        they became the 38th Street Congregational Church. The church merged with the Church of the
        Open Door Congregational in 1950. The church voted to join the United Church of Christ in
        1961. The following year, the church sold its real estate and dissolved as a corporation,
        with most of the congregation voting to join the Lynnhurst Congregational Church.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>This collection contains administrative records of the 38th Street Open Door Congregational
        Church and one of its immediate predecessors, the 38th Street Congregational Church. Those
        records include admission and dismission correspondence, meeting minutes, financial reports,
        and committee and pastor's reports. Notable documents include votes to join the United
        Church of Christ and records pertaining to the dissolution of the church as a corporation
        and sale of its real estate.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>Records in this collection have been arranged chronologically by start date.</p>
    </arrangement>
